      "content": "The Civil Rights Movement in the United States, spanning the 1950s and 1960s, aimed to end racial segregation and discrimination against African Americans. Key stages include the Montgomery Bus Boycott (1955-1956), James Meredith's March Against Segregation (1962), the Birmingham Campaign (1963), the March on Washington (1963), and the Selma to Montgomery Marches (1965). Major legal victories include the Civil Rights Act (1964) and the Voting Rights Act (1965), which legislated the end of segregation and enforced voting rights. The movement led to greater civil rights protections and significant progress toward racial equality in the US.",
